---
id: the_commons
title: Founding the Commons
weight: 10
---

=== intro

A hundred of you arrive at the river's bend, carts empty, the
old country behind you. Night is falling. Before anything else,
the assembly must decide where to lay the first stone.

The vote is yours — all of you, together.

* [Build on the high bluff, safe from floods]
  ~ site = bluff
  -> bluff

* [Build by the water, close to the mill and the fish]
  ~ site = river
  -> river

* [Split the difference — homes on the slope between]
  ~ site = slope
  -> slope

=== bluff

Wind-scoured but dry. From up here you can see every road in.
By spring the walls are up and no flood will ever touch you —
though the climb to the water is long, and it makes you few.

Winter comes hard. A wagon of grain arrives at the gate, and
its driver asks the price of shelter.

* [Open the gates — a commons turns no one away]
  ~ creed = open
  -> reckoning

* [Charge for the night — the stores are thin]
  ~ creed = toll
  -> reckoning

=== river

The water gives freely — fish, reeds, the mill's slow turning.
The commons grows fat and loud and generous, and everyone who
drifts downstream stays a while.

Then the thaw. The river rises brown over the doorsills.

* [Rebuild together, higher, and share the loss]
  ~ creed = open
  -> reckoning

* [Let each house fend for its own]
  ~ creed = toll
  -> reckoning

=== slope

A compromise, and like most compromises it asks more of everyone.
The climb is shorter, the flood-line closer; the assembly meets
twice as often just to settle who owes what to whom.

Strangely, it works — the arguing IS the government.

* [Write the arguments down, so the record outlives you]
  ~ creed = open
  -> reckoning

* [Trust the elders to remember]
  ~ creed = toll
  -> reckoning

=== reckoning

Ten years on, a child of the commons asks how it all began.
The answer depends on what you chose, and who you chose to be.

* [Tell them the truth, and let them vote on what comes next]
  -> ending_open

* [Tell them the founders knew best]
  -> ending_closed

=== ending_open

You tell them everything — the floods, the tolls, the long cold
argument that never quite ended. "We wrote it all down," you say,
"so no one could pretend it happened differently. Now it's yours
to decide." The child nods, and calls the assembly to order.

A commons is not a place. It is a chain of decisions no one can
quietly rewrite. THE END.

=== ending_closed

You smooth the story into something cleaner than it was. The child
believes it. So does their child. By the third generation no one
remembers the vote at the river's bend, only that the founders were
wise, and that it is not their place to ask.

The commons stands. Whether it is still a commons, no one is left
to say. THE END.
